
[1]ladder

   LAD'DER, n.

   1. A frame of wood, consisting of two side pieces, connected by rounds
   inserted in them at suitable distances, and thus forming steps, by
   which persons may ascend a building, &c.

   2. That by which a person ascends or rises; means of ascending; as a
   ladder made of cords.

   Lowliness is young ambition's ladder.

   3. Gradual rise; elevation.

   Mounting fast towards the top of the ladder ecclesiastical.
